\begin_layout Title
Borel Hierarchy for the Cantor Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
1 December 2023
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The Borel hierarchy splits up the creation of a Borel algebra into distinct
 levels, with each level alternating in the number set unions and set complement
s applied.
 This text documents a home-made attempt to write down the lower reaches
 of that hierarchy.
 It fails in a most interesting way: it reveals the need to also take first-orde
r seriously, and perhaps even set theory, when writing down the Borel hierarchy.
 Originally, this text was meant to be a few short, casual paragraphs in
 an appendix to the Vitali paper.
 It exploded as I tried to make things more precise, until it finally collapsed
 under the realization that even this level of precision is not enough.
\end_layout

