\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preliminary remarks about logic and set theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The style of the text below is casual but detailed; it seems to say nothing
 difficult or important, but uses an awful lot of words to do this.
 This came as a sruprise to the author, and some explanation is needed.
 At first, this section was meant to be a few short paragraphs stating the
 well-known and obvious.
 A few shallow and trite properties.
 Attempting to remain precise resulted in an avalanche of algebra.
 This came as a surprise: it was unexpected and unwanted, and yet, it materializ
ed.
 It seemed strange that something so simple, almost trite, could be so wordy.
 It accidentally, unintentionally revealed a deeper truth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lesson of the avalanche is that this homework exercise should have been
 done far more carefully.
 Each verbal statement should be replaced by an expression of first-order
 logic.
 This would reveal the complexity of the statement.
 Each such expression could, in turn, be checked against the axioms of set
 theory, to pin down exactly which axioms are at play.
 Doing so would change the nature of the below entirely, and make it far,
 far longer and wordier still.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the text below was written, attempting to avoid set differences
 and set intersections.
 In this, it mostly succeeds.
 Both the set difference symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\backslash$
\end_inset

, and the set-intersection symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset

 do appear in the text, but they usually can be understood to be just labels,
 simplified stand-ins for earlier statements about certian countale unions.
 That is, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\backslash$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset

 are to be interpeted as short-hand for wordier expressions, rather than
 being literal, concrete operations on sets.
 Unfortunately, this text is a bit vague and sloppy, and so this might not
 always be clear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A different issue has to do with minimum description lengths, and hidden
 axioms and assumptions disguised in verbal text.
 By not using set intersections, the problem of accidentally using infinite
 intersections seems to be avoided.
 Yet, hidden computations lurk in the text.
 Some of the English-language sentences, are they algorithms? If so, what
 is their run-time? What is the complexity class? Perhaps the language of
 effective set theory should have been used?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All this only became clear in hindsight.
 Thus, this text is unsatisfying: verbose, yet lacking precision and rigor.
 Verbose, but explaining obvious and trite concepts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cantor space vs.
 Baire space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of the work is done with the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, but each of the constructions would seem to have an analogous form in
 Baire space, from what I can tell.
 The primary complication is that, given a single digits of a sequence in
 Baire space, it's negation is the rest of the natural numbers, instead
 of a singleton.
 The nice thing about Cantor space is that each digit is 0 or 1, both singletons
, so if its not one.
 its the other.
 Well, that, and the canonical measure on Baire space is trickier.
 We stick to Cantor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choice of notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 is perhaps unfortunate, as it risks confusion with the boldface pointclass
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Delta}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Fortunately, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Delta}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is almost never mentioned.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The base for the topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write the set of all finite strings just as before, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{S}=\left\{ q\vert q=\left(q_{k}\right)_{k=1}^{N}\mbox{for }N<\infty\right\} \cup\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset

and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ext}:\mathbb{S}\to\Delta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ext}:s\mapsto s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 as the extension of any finite string 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $*=\left\{ 0\right\} \cup\left\{ 1\right\} =\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 being the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

don't care
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wildcard bit marker.
 The ext function 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extends
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 finite strings to open sets.
 This provides the definition of the base of the topology: the base is given
 precisely by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ext}s=s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The base is countable, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 is countable.
 The convetional measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on the Cantor space can be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\mbox{ext}s\right)=2^{-\mbox{len}s}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exclusion of zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first example constructs an open set that does not contain the point
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 but does contain every other point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 This will be given by the tree 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\bigcup_{k=0}^{\infty}0^{k}1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{k}$
\end_inset

 is a string of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 zeros in a row.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $z\subset\mathbb{P}_{0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\mathbb{P}_{0}}}$
\end_inset

 as defined earlier.
 The corresponding extension to the Cantor space is 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\mbox{ext}z\subset\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 This is articulated in gory detail below; it corresponds to a union of
 open sets, none of which contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 but which do encroach upon it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define a sequence of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $o_{k}=\mbox{ext}0^{k}1=0^{k}1\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 that are each disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $o_{k}\cap\overline{0}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 because the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

'th bit differs, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 These are also pairwise disjoint, so that that 
\begin_inset Formula $o_{k}\cap o_{j}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 whenver 
\begin_inset Formula $j\ne k$
\end_inset

.
 Consider finally the infinite union of all of these sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\bigcup_{k=0}^{\infty}o_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\cap\overline{0}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 Also by construction, any other point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p\ne\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 This is easily seen by looking at the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 letters 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in o_{0}$
\end_inset

; otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 and perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}=1$
\end_inset

, which would place 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in o_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Extending, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k+1}=0^{k}1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in o_{k}$
\end_inset

 (and the converse: if and only if).
 From this, conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=Z\cup\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 or equivalently, written as set subtraction, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\Delta\backslash\overline{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is open, being the countable union of open sets, and thus is of rank one
 in the boldface Borel hierarchy: 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}$
\end_inset

 is a closed set, belonging as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result can be confirmed by looking at the canonical measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 This gives that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(o_{k}\right)=2^{-\left(k+1\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 From this, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(Z\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\mu\left(o_{k}\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}2^{-\left(k+1\right)}=1
\]

\end_inset

and so (of course) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\overline{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 No surprise; a lot of hot air to say something trivial.
 The above is almost entirely an exercise in defining unambiguous notation,
 and almost nothing more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exclusion of a general point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same construction can be generalized to any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\Delta$
\end_inset

 to obtain an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\Delta\backslash p$
\end_inset

.
 This is built up as 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\bigcup_{k=0}^{\infty}P_{k}$
\end_inset

 the infinite union of pair-wise disjoint open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Each open set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}=\mbox{ext}\left(\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}\check{p}_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined to be disjoint from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The notation here is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{p}_{k}=\neg p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the negation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th bit in the string 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the base of the topology, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding tree is 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\bigcup_{k=0}^{\infty}P_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 As before, this gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\Delta\backslash p$
\end_inset

.
 Just as before, one can verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cap P_{k}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\cap P_{j}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $j\ne k$
\end_inset

, and that all other points 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta,q\ne p$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in P_{k}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, obtained by examining the prefixes of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 The measure works likewise: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(P_{k}\right)=2^{-\left(k+1\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is built from a countable union, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sneaky set intesections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A note of caution is in order.
 The defintion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}$
\end_inset

 as the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 letters of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 appears to be totally innocuous.
 In fact, it is a sneaky introduction of set intersection, since it could
 also be wrtien out as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}=p\cap*^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, both above and below, we've carefully hidden a kind of an interestion
 function in a kind of sneaky way.
 Is it a set intersection? Well, yes, since 
\begin_inset Formula $*=\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $*^{k}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} \times\cdots\times\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 is most definitely a set, with 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{k}$
\end_inset

 distinct elements.
 Oh dear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{p}_{k}=\neg p_{k}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} \backslash p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a set subtraction, hidden in plain view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, everything above, and what follows below, is claimed to only ever
 use countable unions, and never any set intersections, is built on a foundation
 of lies: the use of set intersection was hidden in the English language,
 where it is not immediately visible.
 Saying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

take the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 letters of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 doesn't sound like something harmful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, take everything above and below with a grain of salt.
 Either there's a countably infinite number of set intersections sneakily
 hidden away, or there are not.
 Everything written above and below was written before this realization
 of sneaky intersections.
 Thus, everything that is said is true (I beleive all the algebra and argumentat
ion is correct) but everything is suspect, because of this intesction.
 Further commentary just before the concluding subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Complements of finite unions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several curious questions follow.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}=\bigcup_{k=0}^{n}P_{k}$
\end_inset

 be an intersection of a finite number of open sets.
 By defintion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Can we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is closed, and thus an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

? Lets give it a whirl.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{n}=\bigcup_{k=n+1}^{\infty}P_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Its a countable union of open sets, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{n}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 From before, deduce 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\mathcal{P}_{n}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 One concludes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\mathcal{P}_{n}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}\cup p$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{n}=\mathcal{Q}_{n}\cup p$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $p\notin\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 which leaves the status of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{n}$
\end_inset

 unclear.
 This is resolved shortly below; yes, it will be in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preparing a drawing of a binary tree, with a fixed-length string on it,
 would make all of the above definitions much easier to understand and visualize.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Base neighborhood filter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets try a different approach.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}=\mbox{ext}\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k+1}=\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k+1}\overline{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in O_{k}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a filter of open neighborhoods of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, converging to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, each half the size of the once before.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k+1}\subset O_{k}$
\end_inset

is a proper subset, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(O_{k}\right)=2^{-\left(k+1\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the base of the topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convergence can be seen as follows.
 Consider some point, any point 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 If the first digit of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the same as the first digit of 
\begin_inset Formula $p,$
\end_inset

that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor q\right\rfloor _{1}=\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{1}=p_{1}$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in O_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If the first digits are not the same, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor q\right\rfloor _{1}=\check{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in P_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Appearently, one concludes that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}\cap O_{0}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=P_{0}\cup O_{0}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash P_{0}=O_{0}$
\end_inset

 and vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same argument extends recursively.
 Assume that there exists some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor q\right\rfloor _{k+1}\ne\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k+1}$
\end_inset

; without loss of generality, let this be the least such integer.
 If it does not exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in O_{k}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor q\right\rfloor _{k}=\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}$
\end_inset

 (because 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 was the least) and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k+1}\ne q_{k+1}=\check{p}_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 can only be zero or one, duh.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}\check{p}_{k+1}\overline{*}=\mbox{ext}\left(\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k}\check{p}_{k+1}\right)=P_{k}$
\end_inset

 and similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin O_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This concludes the proof of convergence; if 
\begin_inset Formula $q\ne p$
\end_inset

 then there exists some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin O_{k}$
\end_inset

 and so the filter 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ O_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

 does not converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Complements of neighborhood filters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not hard to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\cap O_{k}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

, since, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in P_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in O_{k}$
\end_inset

 one must have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k+1}\ne y_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 by construction.
 Similarly, the union 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\cup O_{k}$
\end_inset

 includes both possibilities, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\cup O_{k}=O_{k-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This allows fiddling with set subtraction 
\emph on
ad nauseum
\emph default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k-1}\backslash O_{k}=P_{k}$
\end_inset

 and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Returning to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}=\bigcup_{k=0}^{n}P_{k}$
\end_inset

, one concludes that, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\Delta$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathcal{P}_{n}$
\end_inset

 or that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in O_{n}$
\end_inset

, but not both.
 From this, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\mathcal{P}_{n}\cup O_{n}$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}\cap O_{n}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{n}=O_{n}$
\end_inset

 and vice-versa.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{n}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous section noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\mathcal{P}_{n}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}\cup p$
\end_inset

 while now we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\mathcal{P}_{n}\cup O_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}\cap O_{n}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}\cap\mathcal{Q}_{n}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

, it seems safe to conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}=\mathcal{Q}_{n}\cup p$
\end_inset

, and that this conclusion can be reached without having to take any actual
 set intersections, without taking any differences, and without actually
 computing the union of a point.
 From what I can tell, this conclusion is reached entirely via countable
 unions.
 I suppose it all would have been clearer, if we were even more pedantic,
 and clearly stated that the set difference symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\backslash$
\end_inset

 is used above as a notational device, as a short-hand symbol for some equivalen
ce and membership relations, rather than as an actual, concrete difference.
 Likewise, the intersection symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset

 is also being used as a notational device for a (countable) collection
 of predicates, rather than as an actual, concrete intersection operation.
 Unfortunately, most of this is not very clear, as we've never actually
 used predicate-logic expressions to construct any of these sets, nor have
 we taken the effort to examine precisely which set-theory axioms were deployed
 at each step.
 So all this is quite cavalier with the constructions; this entire section
 could be made far more verbose and daunting, by re-writing it to explicitly
 track predicates from first-order logic and from set theory.
 So it goes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At any rate, some of the lowest rank of the Borel hierarchy can be filled
 in: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{n}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 while both 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}$
\end_inset

 are both in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and also in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

; they are clopen sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this, deduce that every set in the base of the topology is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically, let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 be a finite-length string, of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

.
 Then consider 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}=\mbox{ext}s=s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is both clearly a member of the base of the topology, and also a member
 of any neighborhood filter of points starting with the string 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Complements of the base
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may continue down this path just a bit farther, for the sake of completeness.
 Following the earlier construction, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash P_{k}=p\cup\check{P}_{k}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{P}_{k}=\mathcal{P}_{k-1}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Absorbing that one single point, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash P_{k}=p\cup\mathcal{P}_{k-1}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{k}=\mathcal{P}_{k-1}\cup O_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Although this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

looks like
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a union with a closed set 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, it is not; the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}=\mathcal{Q}_{n}\cup p$
\end_inset

 was established above, without appeal to the closed nationer of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So again, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash P_{k}=\mathcal{P}_{k-1}\cup O_{k}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

, as its a countable union.
 But this can also be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}=\Delta\backslash\left(\mathcal{P}_{k-1}\cup O_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is clopen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, it seems that perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{k}\notin\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Can this be proved? Yes.
 From the above, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=p\cup\mathcal{P}_{k}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{k}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\left(\mathcal{P}_{k}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{k}\right)=\left(\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{k}\right)\cap\left(\Delta\backslash Q_{k}\right)=p$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we've already seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{P}_{k}=O_{k}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Proof by contradiction: Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{k}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 This would imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{Q}_{k}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

, which would imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 But that cannot be true; points are not unions of open sets, the assumption
 was wrong, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{k}\notin\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 From this, one can immediately conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}\nsubseteq\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is not an elegant proof, because it invokes intersection, for the first
 time ever.
 We haven't yet worked out what the properties of intersection are (we have
 to assume it distributes over complementation; that's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but weird in the current context.) Finally, we are requested to make an
 awkward deduction from it.
 So, an ugly proof, but adequate for present purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{Q}_{k}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

, we can deduce that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{Q}_{k}$
\end_inset

 are examples of closed sets having a finite measure.
 They are the result of a one point compactification: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{Q}_{k}=p\cup\mathcal{P}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Complements of two points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above notational gymnastics provide just enough limberness to construct
 an open set that includes all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, except for a finite number of points.
 Without loss of generality, the construction is done for two points.
 A tweak of notation is required.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\Delta,a\ne b$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ O_{i}^{a}:0\le i<\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ O_{i}^{b}:0\le i<\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

 denote the basic neighborhhood filters for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

; likewise, all other symbols defined earlier can be similarly superscripted.
 As before, there is some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}=\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor _{n}$
\end_inset

 but the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n+1\right)$
\end_inset

'th digit does not match: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n+1}\ne\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor _{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that not only is 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin O_{k}^{b}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ge n$
\end_inset

, but also that that 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}^{a}\cap O_{k}^{b}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 As a special case, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}^{a}\cap O_{n}^{b}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider next the set 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{a}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\le n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 share a common prefix for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\le n$
\end_inset

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{m}^{a}=P_{m}^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Restricting further to 
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset

, one has, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin P_{m}^{a}$
\end_inset

, but also that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin P_{m}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 This breaks down at 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in P_{n}^{b}$
\end_inset

 and vice-versa, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in P_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Employing the notation from before, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}=\mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{b}=\bigcup_{m=0}^{n-1}P_{m}^{a}$
\end_inset

 has the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}$
\end_inset

 (obviously, as this is true by definition for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) but also that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin\mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 was chosen as the index beyond which the sequences diverge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the point where the bit-sequences diverge, the open covers diverge
 as well, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin P_{k}^{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin P_{k}^{a}$
\end_inset

 holds again, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

.
 Working with the excluded regions is safe.
 Reusing notation from before, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{a}=\bigcup_{k=n+1}^{\infty}P_{k}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

 (holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n)$
\end_inset

 but also 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 was selected as the location after which the sequences diverge.
 To conclude, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{a,b}=\mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{a}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{b}$
\end_inset

 has the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin P^{a,b}$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $b\notin P^{a,b}$
\end_inset

 but that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\cup b\cup P^{a,b}= & a\cup b\cup\mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{a}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{n}^{b}\\
= & \mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}\cup O_{n}^{a}\cup O_{n}^{b}\\
= & \mathcal{P}_{n-1}^{a}\cup O_{n-1}^{a}\\
= & \Delta
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{a,b}=\Delta\backslash\left(a\cup b\right)$
\end_inset

 as desired.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{a,b}$
\end_inset

 was formed entirely from countable unions of open sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{a,b}\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third line above made use of the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}^{a}\cup O_{n}^{b}=O_{n-1}^{a}=O_{n-1}^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 This follows, as the two downard branches join at 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so, as before 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}=\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor _{n}$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n+1}\ne b_{n+1}=\check{a}_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 At this join, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n+1}\cup\check{a}_{n+1}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} =*$
\end_inset

 and so the join is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
O_{n}^{a}\cup O_{n}^{b}= & \left(\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n+1}\overline{*}\right)\cup\left(\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor _{n+1}\overline{*}\right)\\
= & \left(\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}a_{n+1}\overline{*}\right)\cup\left(\left\lfloor b\right\rfloor _{n}b_{n+1}\overline{*}\right)\\
= & \left(\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}a_{n+1}\overline{*}\right)\cup\left(\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}\check{a}_{n+1}\overline{*}\right)\\
= & \left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}\left(a_{n+1}\cup\check{a}_{n+1}\right)\overline{*}\\
= & \left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{n}\overline{*}\\
= & O_{n-1}^{a}=O_{n-1}^{b}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In analogy to the earlier one point compactification result: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{Q}_{k}^{p}=p\cup\mathcal{P}_{k}^{p}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 (which hold for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

), one can construct sets that require two points to compactify.
 In the present case, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\left(\mathcal{Q}_{k}^{a}\cup\mathcal{Q}_{k}^{b}\right)=a\cup b\cup\mathcal{P}_{k}^{a}\cup\mathcal{P}_{k}^{b}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ge n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Complements of any number of points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the general case of three or more points, one needs to find and track
 the branch-points.
 The simplest description for how to do this seems to be algorithmic.
 Define a branching function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{bra}:\mathbb{S}\times\mathcal{P}\left(\Delta\right)\to\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 that determines whether all binary strings in a set 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subset\Delta$
\end_inset

 that begin with a finite string 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 have a common digit at location just past the end of the string 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{brn}:\left(s,L\right)\mapsto\max\left\{ a_{n}\oplus b_{n}:n=1+\mbox{len}s\,,\,a,b\in L\cap s\overline{*}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

In the above expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1+\mbox{len}s$
\end_inset

 identifies the bit position just past the end of the string 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $L\cap s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 is the set of all points in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that have a prefix that is 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 This might be the empty set, in which case the function brn is undefined.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\oplus b_{n}$
\end_inset

 is just the xor of the two bits at location 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

; it is zero, if the two bits are the same, else it is one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sneaks in
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a concrete intersection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset

, but it does so in a way that it does not seem to be directly implicated
 in the rest of the construction.
 Further comments on this sneakery in the next subsection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagined as an algorithm, this must loop over all pairs of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $L\cap s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

, checking if bit location 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 differs.
 If such a pair is found, then the function can return 1 immediately, else
 it needs to keep looping, possible forever, if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is countable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is uncountable, then this is even harder.
 This function carries a lot of water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define a set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\left\{ s\in\mathbb{S}:0=\mbox{brn}\left(s,L\cap s\overline{*}\right)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

This set is countable, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 is countable.
 For any given 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in B$
\end_inset

, define the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{s}^{L}=\bigcup_{a\in L\cap s\overline{*}}P_{\mbox{len}s}^{a}
\]

\end_inset

where, as before, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}^{a}=\mbox{ext}\left(\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{k}\check{a}_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is countable, then the union is countable.
 In fact, the union is overkill, since 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mbox{len}s}^{a}=P_{\mbox{len}s}^{b}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in L\cap s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The above at least avoids having to say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pick a representative 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in L\cap s\overline{*}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin P_{s}^{L}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in L$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the points 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in L$
\end_inset

 are visualized as infinite paths through the infinite binary tree, then
 
\begin_inset Formula $L\cap s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 are all the points that took a common path along 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Having reached the end of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, there are two possibilities: either all of the paths take just one branch,
 or some take one and some take another.
 If only one branch is taken, then 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}^{L}$
\end_inset

 is the branch not taken.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set that exludes all points in 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subset\Delta$
\end_inset

 is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P^{L}=\bigcup_{s\in B}P_{s}^{L}
\]

\end_inset

where, again, at most a countable number of unions is involved, even if
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 was uncountable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The need to construct the branch function, and the set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can be avoided by using the concrete intersection operator.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{s}^{L}=\bigcap_{a\in L\cap s\overline{*}}P_{\mbox{len}s}^{a}
\]

\end_inset

which then has one of two possible values: the same 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}^{L}$
\end_inset

 as before, when 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in B$
\end_inset

, and otherwise the empty set.
 The set that excludes 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P^{L}=\bigcup_{s\in\mathbb{S}}P_{s}^{L}
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 isn't finite, then this variant employs a countale (or more) number of
 intersections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Commentary about the implicit use of set intersection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last section rests on sneakery of the use of intersection.
 The earlier definition hid it in a function, where it seemed to be harmless.
 In the second part, it is made overt.
 And yet, it is used in a way that is incredibly weak: it is not used to
 carve out, subtract parts of some set; it is instead used as an all-of-nothing
 indicator function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It seems strange.
 Everything in this section is about pruning; starting with the infinite
 binary tree, we attempt to explicitly name all subtrees that have no paths
 running through them, and then collect all of them up.
 As there are only countably many of these, we can say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a hah, just take a countable union of them to get the answer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 And yet, it would seem that this is just cleverly disgused set subtraction.
 The subtraction is done with English-language sentences, which say things
 like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

consider everything that isn't this thing here
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which is plainly a subtraction when written this way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The very defintion of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}^{a}=\mbox{ext}\left(\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{k}\check{a}_{k+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 involves a carfully hidden set subtraction.
 Instead of using the innocuous-looking defintion 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{k}$
\end_inset

 be the first 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 bits of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, lets write it out:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{k}=a\cap*^{k}
\]

\end_inset

Whoops: a cleverly hidden intersection!.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{a}_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 can also be seen as a clverly hidden set subtraction, a kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

take everything that is not this
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Recall the definition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{a}_{k}=\neg a_{k}=\left\{ 0,1\right\} \backslash a_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a set subtraction, hidden in plain view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apparently, using casual English allows very sneaky and subversive operations
 to be performed, that violate the spirit of the Borel hierarachy as being
 phrased entirely in terms of unions, with no set intersections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just how pervasive is the damage? It seems that the defintion of the base
 of the topology is safe: it just says that the base is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ext}s=s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the open neighborhood filter of a point is suspect.
 Given a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the filter was built from open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}^{p}=\mbox{ext}\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k+1}=\left\lfloor p\right\rfloor _{k+1}\overline{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, each one of these open sets is identical to some distinct set, selected
 from the base topology.
 It is a singleton.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}^{p}$
\end_inset

 was intended to define how to choose, how to select basic sets, and nothing
 more.
 But such a definition is an intersection at a meta-level: write the base
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{B}=\left\{ s\overline{*}:s\in\mathbb{S}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

Then the neighborhood filter is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O^{p}=\left\{ x\in\mathcal{B}:p\in x\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

which is further stratified by size:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{k}^{p}=\left\{ x\in O^{p}:\mu\left(x\right)=2^{-k}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

But there's some hidden intersection here.
 Write instead
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{B}_{k}=\left\{ x\in\mathcal{B}:\mu\left(x\right)=2^{-k}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

and then one has 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}^{p}=O^{p}\cap\mathcal{B}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Is this an intersection, or isn't it? It's not an intersection in the sense
 of intersection sets in Cantor space; it happens at a meta-level, and is
 carefully crafted so that we wouldn't need to actually intersect subsets
 of the Cantor space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What a freakin mess.
 The long and painful lesson here appears to be this: Discussion of the
 Borel hierarchy is vacuous, unless it is founded on predicate calculus
 and first-order logic.
 Perhaps one can convince onself that one is being very careful, and make
 persuasive arguments that all of ones claims are well-founded.
 But this hardly seems obvious at this point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these sentences, I close this text fortwith.
 I'm disgusted.
 I've learned something, but the lesson is that this whole collection of
 ideas is deeper and more complex than one might naively imagine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What was the point of this lengthly and tedious exposition? Well, lets see:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The base for the topology was made explicit; it consists of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ext}s=s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathbb{S}=2^{<\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 It is countable, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}$
\end_inset

 is countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The base for the topology was sufficient to build a neighborhood filter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ O_{k}^{a}\right\} $
\end_inset

 for every point 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 The members of the filter are 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}^{a}=\mbox{ext}\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{k+1}=\left\lfloor a\right\rfloor _{k+1}\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 and there is a countable number of them: every point has a countable base.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are multiple examples of pairs of open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 constructed so that they are complements, with 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B=\Delta$
\end_inset

, and both 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 were explicitly constructed as countable unions, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, these are clopen sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Set intersection was not needed to build any of the examples in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The examples all have a very short description length; starting from finite-leng
th strings, one needs only a handful of additional operations to describe
 the examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individual points 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 belong to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 pointclass, as do many open sets, including the base of the topology, and
 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some of the open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{k}^{a}\notin\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}\nsubseteq\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\backslash\mathcal{Q}_{k}^{a}\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 are examples of closed sets that are not points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not much particularly intersing is learned here, except perhaps the last
 two or three bullets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}\nsubseteq\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is a generic property of uncountable Polish sets.
 For every ordinal 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

, it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{0}\nsubseteq\mathbf{\Pi}_{\alpha}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pointclass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{2}^{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pointclass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is defined with set complementation: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}\backslash A\in\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Explict examples of sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

 were given above; they were the individual points 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, and also 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n}^{a}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 Most importantly, the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $s\overline{*}$
\end_inset

 from the base of the topology are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pointclass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{2}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is expressed as consisting of countable unions of the members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the base of the topology is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Pi}_{1}^{0}$
\end_inset

, one can immediately conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{1}^{0}\subset\mathbf{\Sigma}_{2}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What interesting things can we build from countable unions of these? Not
 sure what I can say here.
\end_layout

